South Korea Stocks: Hana Financial, Hyundai Heavy, LG Chem

-- B y   S a e r o m i   S h i n
-- 
2011-07-21T00:30:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-21/south-korea-stocks-hana-financial-hyundai-heavy-lg-chem.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  South Korea  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 9:20 a.m. in  Seoul . The  Kospi
Index (KOSPI)  fell 8.27, or 0.4 percent, to 2,146.68.  Hana Financial Group Inc. (086790)  (086790 KS), the South Korean
lender that’s trying to buy Korea Exchange Bank, rallied 1.4
percent to 38,750 won. Second-quarter profit more than doubled
on gains from selling its stake in a construction company and a
wider lending margin. Net income climbed to 482.6 billion won
($457 million) in the three months ended June 30 from a revised
199.7 billion won a year earlier, according to a filing.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS), the world’s
biggest shipbuilder, tumbled 3.8 percent to 415,500 won, set for
the lowest close since June 20. Profit in the second quarter
dropped 17 percent as it built more ships that were won at lower
prices after the credit crisis. Net income fell to 538.8 billion
won from a restated 645.4 billion won a year earlier, according
to a filing based on parent figures.  LG Chem Ltd. (051910)  (051910 KS), South Korea’s biggest chemicals
maker, sank 4.4 percent to 472,000 won. The company posted a 3.3
percent decline in second-quarter profit, missing analyst
estimates, as demand for materials used to make notebooks and
mobile phones weakened. Net income declined to 624.5 billion won
in the three months ended June 30 from 645.7 billion won a year
earlier, according to a filing.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Saeromi Shin in Seoul at 
